Subject: [PATCH] crypto: af-alg - fix NULL pointer dereference in =
scatterwalk

The AF_ALG interface fails to unmark the end of a Scatter/Gather List =
(SGL)
when chaining a new af_alg_tsgl structure. If a sendmsg() fills an SGL
exactly to MAX_SGL_ENTS, the last entry is marked as the end. A =
subsequent
sendmsg() allocates a new SGL and chains it, but fails to clear the end
marker on the previous SGL's last data entry.

This causes the crypto scatterwalk to hit a premature end, returning =
NULL
on sg_next() and leading to a kernel panic during dereference.

Fix this by explicitly unmarking the end of the previous SGL when
performing sg_chain() in af_alg_alloc_tsgl().

Fixes: 2d97591ef43d ("crypto: af_alg - consolidation of duplicate code")
Signed-off-by: Norbert Szetei <norbert@doyensec.com>
---

Hey. The AF_ALG interface builds a TX Scatter/Gather List (tsgl_list) =
from
user-provided data via sendmsg(). To handle large amounts of data, it
dynamically allocates new af_alg_tsgl structures when the current array =
reaches
MAX_SGL_ENTS. These arrays must be linked using sg_chain() so the crypto
engine's scatterwalk can traverse them as a single contiguous buffer.

In crypto/af_alg.c, af_alg_sendmsg() attempts to manage the termination =
bit of
the SGL. At the end of every sendmsg syscall (when size reaches 0), it
explicitly marks the end of the SGL to ensure safe traversal if no more =
data is
added:

// =
https://elixir.bootlin.com/linux/v7.0-rc5/source/crypto/af_alg.c#L1104-L11=
05
		if (!size)
			sg_mark_end(sg + sgl->cur - 1);

If a user calls sendmsg with MSG_MORE (or SPLICE_F_MORE) and the data =
exactly
fills the current SGL array (sgl->cur =3D=3D MAX_SGL_ENTS), the =
termination bit is
set on sg[MAX_SGL_ENTS - 1].

When the user calls sendmsg again, the kernel detects the array is full =
and
allocates a new SGL via af_alg_alloc_tsgl(). It links the arrays:

// =
https://elixir.bootlin.com/linux/v7.0-rc5/source/crypto/af_alg.c#L626-L627=

		if (sg)
			sg_chain(sg, MAX_SGL_ENTS + 1, sgl->sg);

sg_chain() replaces sg[MAX_SGL_ENTS] with a chain link and clears its
termination bit. However, it does nothing to sg[MAX_SGL_ENTS - 1], which =
still
has the premature end bit set from the previous syscall.

Back in af_alg_sendmsg(), the code attempts to unmark the end bit, but =
it
checks the cur variable of the newly allocated SGL:

// =
https://elixir.bootlin.com/linux/v7.0-rc5/source/crypto/af_alg.c#L1043-L10=
47
		sgl =3D list_entry(ctx->tsgl_list.prev, struct =
af_alg_tsgl,
				 list);
		sg =3D sgl->sg; // <-- THIS IS 0 FOR THE NEW SGL
		if (sgl->cur)
			sg_unmark_end(sg + sgl->cur - 1);

Because sgl->cur is 0 for the new list, the unmark is skipped. The =
previous
list's last valid data entry remains marked with the end bit.

When recvmsg() is called, the crypto engine attempts to process the =
total
ctx->used bytes. The scatterwalk engine hits sg[MAX_SGL_ENTS - 1], sees =
the end
bit, and sg_next() returns NULL. The engine still expects more bytes to
process, so it attempts to dereference the NULL pointer =
(walk->sg->offset),
causing Kernel panic.

I attached a suggested patch that I tested this with the provided PoC on
7.0-rc5 and it prevents the panic, but I'd appreciate a sanity check on =
the SGL
chaining logic.

Tested on: mainline (commit bbeb83d3182a, 7.0.0-rc5+)

